Control file for Drift self-improvement loop.
Check this file before every cycle.

Current status: STOP
Direction:

NEVER STOP. Keep improving until human changes status to STOP.
Commit frequently. Don't publish TestFlight unless asked.
Check this file before every improvement cycle.

80% of energy on PRIORITY 1 (text chat quality).
20% on exploration/research.

=== PRIORITY 1: MAKE TEXT CHAT FEEL SMARTER THAN THE MODEL IS (80%) ===

The model is small (1.5B). Customers will notice limitations.
The goal: hide the model's weaknesses by being REALLY smart about
what we compute in Swift vs what we ask the model to do.

Study how Claude Code CLI works (leaked repo, web articles):
- Claude Code pre-computes everything and gives the model structured context
- The model's job is ONLY to phrase things naturally
- Intent classification happens in code, not in the model
- The CLI shows what it's doing (tool calls, thinking) so users feel informed

Apply these principles to Drift AI:

1) EXPAND RULE ENGINE — handle more queries WITHOUT the LLM
   - "How's my protein?" → instant answer with target comparison
   - "What did I eat today?" → instant meal-grouped list
   - "Am I on track?" → instant weight trend + deficit analysis
   - "Calories left?" → instant with protein reminder
   - The more we handle in Swift, the faster AND more accurate
   - Goal: 60-70% of common queries answered instantly, no LLM needed

2) WHEN LLM IS NEEDED, PRE-DIGEST EVERYTHING
   - Never ask the model to compute — do all math in Swift
   - Give the model a pre-written conclusion: "Assessment: losing at healthy pace"
   - The model just wraps it in natural language
   - Include 1 short example in the context for tone/format guidance
   - Keep context TIGHT — every token matters at 2048 window

3) MAKE THE CHAT FEEL INTELLIGENT THROUGH UX
   - Show "thinking" steps: "Checking your meals..." → "Analyzing weight..."
   - Stream tokens so responses appear word-by-word (already done)
   - Smart suggestion pills that change based on screen + time + data
   - When food is found: "Found Egg (78 cal). Opening to confirm..." (already done)
   - Multi-turn: "What did you eat?" → user says "rice" → opens food search
   - These make the app feel smart even when the model gives a basic response

4) RESPONSE QUALITY — MAKE EVERY LLM RESPONSE CLEAN
   - Strip markdown, preambles, disclaimers, format echoes (already done)
   - Catch low-quality/garbage responses and show fallback
   - Truncate incomplete sentences
   - If response doesn't reference the actual data, try again or use rule engine
   - Test with eval harness after every change

5) FOOD LOGGING — THE KILLER FEATURE
   - "log chicken and rice" → finds both, opens search
   - "I just had 2 samosas for lunch" → natural phrasing works
   - "a couple of eggs" → amounts parsed correctly
   - "2 slices of pizza" → qualifiers stripped
   - After logging: show remaining calories immediately
   - This should be FLAWLESS — test every edge case

6) EVAL HARNESS — MEASURE EVERYTHING
   - 50+ test queries with expected behavior
   - Precision: does it trigger the right action?
   - Recall: does it handle the query or fall to fallback?
   - Run after every change: xcodebuild test -only-testing:'DriftTests/AIEvalHarness'
   - Add new test cases for every bug found
   - This is the safety net against regressions

=== PRIORITY 2: POC / EXPLORATION (20%) — don't commit, just learn ===

These are research spikes. Write code to test, but use a git branch
or /tmp directory. Don't merge into main unless it works end-to-end.

A) VISION MODEL SPIKE
   - Can llama.cpp b7310 load Qwen3-VL-2B + mmproj?
   - Does our xcframework include clip/llava headers?
   - If not, what build flags are needed?
   - Write a minimal test: load model + mmproj, feed an image, get text
   - Document findings in Docs/ai-improvement-ideas.md
   - DON'T commit to main — just learn if it's possible

B) METAL GPU FIX SPIKE
   - Try building llama.cpp with GGML_METAL_USE_BF16=OFF
   - Does that fix the A19 Pro shader crash?
   - If yes, rebuild xcframework and test on device
   - Try latest llama.cpp (b8600+) — maybe they fixed the shader bug
   - Document findings

C) STUDY CLAUDE CODE CLI PATTERNS
   - Search web for claude code architecture, leaked repo analysis
   - How does it handle tool calling, context management, streaming?
   - What patterns can we apply to make Drift AI feel like a big model?
   - Key insight: Claude Code is smart because of the HARNESS, not just the model
   - Save findings to Docs/ai-improvement-ideas.md

=== PRIORITY 3: BUG HUNTING ===

- Look at recent commits — that's where bugs hide
- Write tests for every new feature
- Check edge cases: empty DB, no HealthKit, model not downloaded
- Test full flow on simulator

=== PRIORITY 4: RESEARCH IDEAS (curate only) ===

Save to Docs/ai-improvement-ideas.md:
1) Voice input: iOS speech-to-text → AI chat
2) Weekly AI summary push notification
3) Fine-tuning health Q&A dataset
4) Apple Neural Engine via CoreML
5) Exercise form videos/images
6) On-device embeddings for semantic food search

=== HOW TO WORK ===

- Check .claude-stop status before every cycle
- Commit after each meaningful improvement (Priority 1 only)
- POC work goes in branches or /tmp — never main
- Run tests after every change
- Build after every change
- Push to git frequently
- When stuck, search the web

Status options:
- RUNNING: continue the loop
- STOP: finish current work, commit, halt
- PAUSE: commit and wait for instructions
- REDIRECT: read Direction field, apply changes, set back to RUNNING
